The paper deals with the problem of multi-robot motion planning, which is a core topic in robotics. The use of model predictive control (MPC) and collision avoidance methods suggests that the paper belongs to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of an event-triggered replanning strategy and simulation results suggest that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of optimization techniques and trajectory generation suggests that the paper may also belong to the Mathematical Optimization (cs.MA) sub-category. The use of machine learning and artificial intelligence techniques is also possible, suggesting that the paper may belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the use of simulation results and experimental validation suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
